The drive through the Talysh Mountains is wildly romantic.
The minibus rumbles along the winding road, past densely forested hills, raging rivers and simple farmhouses.
Everything is green and lush, you might think you are in the Black Forest.
But this is the deepest south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
This is where the Talysh people live, of whom not much is known, except that they speak perfect Persian and Azeri and are very long-lived.
Terminus is Lerik.
The small town flaunts too bulky architecture from Soviet times, which doesn't fit into the picturesque mountain landscape.
Tourists from Europe hardly come here, the journey from Azerbaijan's capital Baku is too difficult.
It takes eight hours for the 323 kilometers because the road is only one lane.
The incredible wealth that the country owes to its oil in the Caspian Sea has not yet arrived here in the province.
But Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May with the Eurovision Song Festival - and next year we have a festival of the oldest people in the world here," says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Longevity Museum, arguably the only one in the world.
Here is the vita of about eight dozen Talysh from the area who are older than 100. Fatulayeva points to a black-and-white photo.
This is my grandfather, he lived to be 120 years old.
Had another child at the age of 136
But the controversial star of the museum is the shepherd ≈ûirali M√ºsl√ºmov, who is said to have lived to the age of 168.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And in view of the oldest documented person, who lived to be 122, M√ºsl√ºmov's age seems extremely doubtful.
"He was born here in the region in 1805 and died in 1973," explains Fatulayeva.
The man had been married three times and had 23 children, at the age of 136 he is said to have fathered a daughter.
So did ≈ûirali M√ºsl√ºmov miscalculate his age by a few decades?
But Rembrandt Scholz, age researcher at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the very old in Central Asia.
"There are also a striking number of very old people in some areas of China, in Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," says Scholz. "There are also an extremely large number of very old men living in Sardinia."
Due to a lack of documents, however, no scientific proof of age could be provided, especially since there were no civil status registers.
Cups of melted butter every day
The fact is, however, that the people in the region around Lerik often reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people older than 100 years.
So why do so many very old people live here in the south?
The Azerian guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains this with the special genes of the Talysh.
Museum director Fatulayeva, on the other hand, believes that it is due to the diet.
But that the high-calorie diet of the Talyschen, who love meat, bread and above all dairy products and many of whom drink a glass of melted butter every day, should be so healthy, does not seem particularly plausible from a nutritional point of view.
Or is it the original way of life that keeps people young? Rubaba Mirzayeva lives in Cengemiran, a tiny settlement not far from the town of Lerik.
At 97, she is still comparatively young for this latitude.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor with a butter churn that she tirelessly rolls back and forth.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, both of whom have long been grandparents.
Two small children are also jumping around.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for the guests, which is served in the typical, bulbous Armadu glasses.
Mirzayeva's white teeth line up perfectly, under her headscarf she hides long, dark-blonde braids, which her son proudly reveals to us.
I always washed my hair with milk so it never ran out and kept its color.
"I never used shampoo either," says Mirzayeva.
Monthly pension is enough to live on
She only ever ate what came from her own farm, tomatoes, potatoes, peas.
I have never once bought groceries from the supermarket in my entire life.
Then she tells about her husband, who was in the army.
It was the worst after World War II.
But everything got better when "beloved father" Heydar Aliyev took over the helm.
The propaganda sounds strange coming from an old woman's mouth.
But the cult surrounding the nation's father figure, who ruled his country like a dictator, knows almost no borders in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, later his son Ilham took over the helm.
After all, there is no need among Azerbaijan's elderly.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats (roughly the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount that is easy to live on by local standards.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's son, who has long since turned gray, is right: "The elderly are held in high esteem in our culture."
They live in the middle of the extended family, are loved, cared for and are happy.
