The word "human rights" is missing from the constitution
The revolution has returned to Cairo.
Rival rallies in Cairo reveal deep divisions in the country.
The future constitution based on Sharia law is hotly disputed.
The Egyptian President did not skimp on pathos.
We have to make the transition.
"And that it succeeds is my responsibility, before the people and before God," he said on state television.
His speech was addressed to the whole people, but above all probably to the Christian Copts, the liberals, enlightened Muslims and seculars.
Because all of them, so far hopelessly at odds in a confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a theocracy on the Nile by the grace of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohammed Morsi said, almost apologetically, that he had temporarily curtailed the powers of the constitutional court and expanded its powers "to save the revolution."
But what the 61-year-old engineer, who holds a doctorate from the American University of Southern California, really wants to save, the Egyptians are not sure about, the world is not quite clear.
Should the judiciary be disempowered?
Indeed, the 234 articles rattled through by the Islamist-dominated 100-strong Constituent Assembly in a late-night, 15-hour tour de force are in part troubling.
As in previous constitutions, the draft states that the judiciary is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
But what does "principles" mean?
That was and is a matter of interpretation, and it is to be feared that the Islamists will use the vague wording and the associated legal leeway for a stricter interpretation of the Sharia.
At least that is what a newly added article suggests: Al-Ashar University, the country's most important Islamic institution with great influence on all of Sunni Islam, must be consulted on all matters relating to Sharia.
This does not have to be, but it can mean that the clergy oversees legislation, effectively incapacitating the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is a matter of interpretation
Also problematic: The civilian military jurisdiction should continue to be maintained.
These courts served to repress opposition figures during Mubarak's rule.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were in military custody.
According to the draft, the state should also protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family and promote their morals and values".
This is formulated so vaguely in legal terms that state institutions could even control the content of film art and literature with the help of this article.
In plain language, this means nothing other than censorship.
Incidentally, no article expressly stipulates equality between men and women.
For this, another forbids insulting or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what constitutes an insult and how it is to be punished remains unclear.
The wording that "insulting people" is forbidden seems just as dubious.
Is a caricature of the president enough or a joke at the expense of a legal scholar?
It's a matter of interpretation, like so much in the draft that Morsi is ready to sign and which he says will be presented to the Egyptians for a referendum "very soon".
"The revolution has returned"
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the supremacy of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual unity on Friday night in Cairo's Tahrir Square and vowed to overthrow the charter before it can come into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-place finisher in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, said the draft constitution "belongs on the garbage heap of history."
Via the short message service Twitter, he accused Morsi's supporters of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy".
"If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," opposition leader Jasser Said said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned for," the Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced they would not oversee the referendum, rendering it invalid.
"The Koran is our constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood blew a counter-demonstration, to be on the safe side, not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other bank of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and Salafist supporters attended, shouting: "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded of Morsi: "Clean up the country!" and affirmed: "The Koran is our constitution."
A fight for sovereignty over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have provoked conditions similar to a civil war.
Morsi's supporters obviously didn't want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood said both those who opposed the draft constitution and those who supported it spoke out loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the Islamists' draft is considered certain.
"The word human rights doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry about this accelerated constitutional process, which should have lasted until February and involved all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and head of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) has defended the Muslim Brotherhood as they were imprisoned and on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights isn't even in the new constitution," he complained in an interview with "Welt am Sonntag".
Mursi's extension of power to all three branches of the state made the lawyer resign.
These measures are blatant violations of the democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto disabling it," Saeda laments.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, which views the ideological struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could take revenge.
A protester on Tahrir warns: "You are giving birth to a monster that you can no longer control."
